<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ephedra</i> <i>californica</i> or <i>Ephedra</i> <i>trifurca</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy in transmontane stands with <i>Adenophyllum</i> <i>cooperi</i>, <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>dumosa</i>, <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>salsola</i>, <i>Cleome</i> <i>isomeris</i>, <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>ramosissima</i>, <i>Larrea</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Lycium</i> <i>andersonii</i> or <i>Senecio</i> <i>flaccidus</i>. Cismontane stands may include <i>Atriplex</i> <i>spinifera</i>, <i>Eastwoodia</i> <i>elegans</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Eriophyllum</i> <i>confertiflorum</i> or <i>Gutierrezia</i> <i>californica</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is open to 
intermittent. Herbaceous lyer is sparse to intermittent with seasonal annuals and perennial grasses. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Ephedra californica</i> ≥ 2% absolute cover in the shrub cover (Evens 2000).</li>
		
		<li><i>Ephedra californica</i> ≥ 2% absolute shrub cover, and dominant or may co-dominate with <i>Gutierrezia californica</i> (Evens et al. 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Ephedra californica</i> dominates, but <i>Ambrosia salsola</i> may be up to two times <i>E. californica</i> cover before placing stands in the <i>Ambrosia salsola</i> alliance (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li><i>Ephedra californica</i> or <i>E. trifurca</i> co-dominant (> 30% relative cover) in the shrub layer; often on loose, sandy soils (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Intermittently flooded arroyos, washes, and adjacent alluvial fans in transmontane settings; residual dunes and xeric fine-grained sedimentary substrates in cismontane settings. Soils are coarse to medium sands, loamy sands, and sandy clay loams.  </div>
</div>

        
