<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> The ecology of <i>Ephedra californica </i>is poorly known. Plants are slow-growing shrubs that spread clonally. As with <i>E. nevadensis, </i>we expect seed set to be variable, and seedling establishment to follow wet years (Anderson 2004a). The underground rhizomes make it well adapted to shifting sand and alluvial substrates. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ephedra californica </i>is a widespread shrub of the hot deserts in other alliances, such as the <i>Atriplex canescens, Atriplex polycarpa, Larrea tridentata-Ambrosia dumosa, Psorothamnus spinosus, </i>and <i>Yucca schidigera </i> alliances. Stands of <i>Ephedra californica </i>alliance are most common on low-gradient wash sites within the similar ecological zone to <i>Ambrosia salsola, </i>but also on slightly less disturbed microsites, such as along low terraces and banks of washes (Evens 2000). Some stands associate with sand sheets, dunes, and other sandy substrates with <i>Achnatherum hymenoides, A. speciosum, Pleuraphis rigida, </i>and mound-forming shrubs.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Ephedra trifurca </i>is one of the most abundant shrubs in other southwestern states but is less common in California. In California, it occurs in the Colorado Desert and southern Mojave Desert in sandy substrates similar to <i>E. californica </i>. Plants are sprawling shrubs that can reach 2 m in height.<br/>
<br/>
This alliance was previously cited as <i>Ephedra californica </i> Shrubland Alliance in the <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>.  Additional classification analyses and surveys from the Death Valley National Park and Moave National Preserve (Evens et al. 2014) have expanded our understanding of the alliance to include additional characteristic species. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
