    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ac-d, Ai-k). Stands in this section are the only ones known that occur regularly in upland settings, and are dominated by <i>Ephedra californica</i>. Those on the Monvero residual dunes (Holland 1986) occur on ancient stabilized diatomaceous substrates. <i>Cleome isomeris</i> and other disjunct desert species, such as <i>Achnatherum hymenoides</i> and <i>Rumex hymenosepalus,</i> grow here (Evens et al. 2006). This alliance occurs extensively around the Carrizo Plain as stands surrounded by annual grasslands  at the basin margins, and continuing on slopes in the Temblor and Caliente Mountains. Toward the western boundary of its range, <i>Ephedra californica</i> stands have been seen in Pine Canyon near Joaquin Ridge. <i>Ephedra californica</i> ranges north to Ortigalita Peak in the Diablo Range.</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-b, Cd). McHargue (1973) found <i>Ephedra californica</i> dominant with <i>Bebbia juncea</i> along washes and rocky bajadas of the Coachella Valley. Stands of <i>Ephedra trifurca</i> have been found southeast of Niland on the East Mesa (Menke et al. 2016) and in the Algodones Dunes (J. Malusa, pers. comm. 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Aq, Az). Stands occur in the washes and surrounding uplands emanating from the Elk Hills. Stands are also found in the Ciervo Hills of western Fresno County (Evens et al. 2006), and on the edges of the Little Panoche Valley (CNPS 2015). In the southeast edge of the San Joaquin Valley, stands have been seen east of  Oildale and Lamont.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ac-p). Stands occur in throughout the section on dissected washes of alluvial fans derived from non-calcareous substrates in Granite Mountains (Evens 2000), and stands occur generally in the central, southern, and eastern subsections (Thomas et al. 2004, Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005). A high concentration of <i>Ephedra californica</i> stands were mapped in small washes surrounding Coyote Dry Land, around Alvord Mountain, and south of Hinkley near the Mojave River (VegCAMP and AIS 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd). Stands are found northeast of Caliente near Tehachapi Pass (VegCAMP 2015a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-c, Be). Stands exist on stabilized dunes in Rice Valley and in washes in the Cadiz-Vidal Valleys subsection (Evens and Hartman 2007; VegCAMP and AIS 2013),  which include <i>Ephedra trifurca</i> as the dominant. Stands of <i>Ephedra californica</i> have been seen in the Chocolate Mountains (J. Malusa, pers. comm. 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bg, Bi-j, Bp). Stands occur throughout the eastern subsections adjacent to the warm deserts.  Stands in this section are dominated by <i>Ephedra californica</i>. It has been sampled and mapped as part of the Sand to Snow project (UC Riverside, in progress) and the Peninsula Bighorn Sheep Habitat map (Menke and Johnson 2016) along the Whitewater River.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Burros and OHVs adversely impact many transmontane stands. Stands in the Monocline Ridge area of Fresno Co are rare and sensitive (CNDDB 2008). </div>
</div>

    

    

